    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-17T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-17T21:00:00-05:00" n="333"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d333">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/26788: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vera Cruz</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wood</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="6" xml:id="d333fn6">John Q. Wood.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vera Cruz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-17T19:00:00-07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 17, 1924—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 18—9:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Have received a circular letter from naval command of <hi rend="italic">de
                        facto</hi> government that it has been decided to mine ports of Frontera,
                    Puerto Mexico and Vera Cruz as necessary measures in the present conflict.
                    Admiral Magruder coming here, now on way, to enter port at night. Pilot should
                    be taken on entering.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wood</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
